{"id":"1903.08663","submitter":"Alexander Streltsov","authors":"Jan Kolodynski, Swapan Rana, Alexander Streltsov","title":"Entanglement negativity as a universal non-Markovianity witness","comments":"6+3 pages, 1 figure, improved presentation of results","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. A 101, 020303(R) (2020)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevA.101.020303","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In order to engineer an open quantum system and its evolution, it is\nessential to identify and control the memory effects. These are formally\nattributed to the non-Markovianity of dynamics that manifests itself by the\nevolution being indivisible in time, a property which can be witnessed by a\nnon-monotonic behavior of contractive functions or correlation measures. We\nshow that by monitoring directly the entanglement behavior of a system in a\ntripartite setting it is possible to witness all invertible non-Markovian\ndynamics, as well as all (also non-invertible) qubit evolutions. This is\nachieved by using negativity, a computable measure of entanglement, which in\nthe usual bipartite setting is not a universal non-Markovianity witness. We\nemphasize further the importance of multipartite states by showing that\nnon-Markovianity cannot be faithfully witnessed by any contractive function of\nsingle qubits. We support our statements by an explicit example of eternally\nnon-Markovian qubit dynamics, for which negativity can witness non-Markovianity\nat arbitrary time scales.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 20 Mar 2019 18:00:03 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 10 Dec 2019 11:22:55 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-03-23"}
